# ADR 0001: Defer adoption of the React Compiler

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-06-23

## Context
The create-next-app scaffold offers the React Compiler, which auto-memoizes
components at build time, largely removing the need for manual useMemo/
useCallback/React.memo. I'm comfortable with React but not advanced, and this
is a small portfolio site.

## Options considered
- Enable: free automatic memoization, but it hides the re-render mechanics I'm
  still learning, and adds magic I can't yet explain in an interview.
- Disable: I handle memoization manually and learn why and when it matters.

## Decision
Disable the React Compiler for now.

## Rationale
I want to understand why re-renders happen and what useMemo/useCallback actually
solve before delegating that to a compiler. At this scale the compiler's benefit
is negligible — enabling it would be optimization with no problem to solve, i.e.
resume-driven, not need-driven.

## Consequences
I'll write memoization by hand where genuinely needed. I commit to revisiting in
Phase 3: profile performance, and adopt the compiler only if measured re-render
overhead justifies it — at which point it becomes a documented, deliberate
optimization rather than a default I never questioned.